EDR — Endpoint Detection and Response

Think of EDR like a very smart CCTV camera installed INSIDE every single computer in your company. It watches every process, file, login, and network connection happening on that machine — 24/7. And unlike a normal camera, it can also fight back.
What is an endpoint?
Endpoints include
Laptops, desktops, servers, mobile devices — any device that connects to your network

Windows servers, Linux servers, Unix endpoints — all monitored by SentinelOne
What does EDR actually do?
Monitors every process running on a machine in real time
Records file creation, modification, deletion — every change
Tracks network connections made from the endpoint
Detects threats using behavioral AI, not just signatures
Isolates infected endpoint from the network instantly
Rolls back all changes malware made — like a time machine
Stores full telemetry for forensic investigation later
The process tree — heart of EDR investigation
Real attack chain you would see in SentinelOne
Word.exe
→
PowerShell.exe
→
cmd.exe
→
net.exe
Word opening PowerShell is ABNORMAL. EDR detects this behavioral pattern and raises a threat — even if the malware is brand new and has no known signature.
EDR vs old antivirus — why EDR is better
Old antivirus
Only blocks KNOWN threats using a signature database. New malware walks right past it.
EDR (SentinelOne)
Detects BEHAVIOR. Even unknown malware gets caught if it acts suspiciously.
Key point for interview: EDR works on the endpoint level. It is your deep visibility into ONE machine at a time — what ran, what changed, what connected where.





XDR — Extended Detection and Response

If EDR is a smart camera in one room, XDR is a command center with cameras in EVERY room — plus the hallways, the front gate, the parking lot, and the phone system — all feeding into ONE screen. One analyst sees everything at once.
What XDR adds on top of EDR
XDR collects data from ALL these sources — not just endpoints
Endpoints (EDR) Email security Firewall logs Cloud workloads Identity/AD Network traffic SIEM Threat intelligence
Why XDR is powerful — a real scenario
Attack that EDR alone might miss — XDR catches it
Step 1 — Attacker sends phishing email (email security sees this)
Step 2 — User clicks link, malware downloads (EDR sees this on endpoint)
Step 3 — Malware talks to C2 server on port 443 (firewall/network sees this)
Step 4 — Attacker logs in using stolen credentials from cloud (identity sees this)

EDR only sees Step 2. XDR sees ALL FOUR steps and connects them into ONE incident timeline — giving you the full attack story automatically.
What XDR does automatically
Correlates alerts from multiple security tools into one single incident
Reduces alert fatigue — 100 alerts become 1 grouped incident
Provides full attack timeline across all layers (email → endpoint → network → cloud)
Uses AI to prioritize which threats need attention first
Allows response from one console — isolate, block, investigate all in one place
Shares threat intelligence across all integrated tools automatically
